# arvo-bitmask — backlog

## cap_size helper promotion to arvo

The cap_size(c: Cap) -> usize const-fn helper currently lives local
to each L2 / L3 crate that uses `const N: Cap` in signatures
(arvo-spectral, and this crate after the 202604260000 cleanup). When
a third consumer lands (arvo-graph, arvo-sparse, or arvo-comb after
their own Cap/USize cleanup rounds), promote the helper into arvo
(L0) as a public const-fn. The promotion is purely additive (no
breaking changes) and eliminates the 3-line duplication.

## Mask256-wide BitMatrix trait abstraction

BitMatrix64 and BitMatrix256 duplicate their set / get / row ops
today. A trait-backed single generic BitMatrix<W, N> would collapse
the duplication but fights `generic_const_exprs` on current nightly
(the same trade-off arvo-sparse records for its `_64` / `_256`
algorithm pair). Revisit when the const-generics feature stabilises
or when a third width (Mask128?) surfaces and makes the duplication
painful.

## BitMatrix iter / arvo-bits BitMatrix contract

A BitMatrix contract in arvo-bits (paralleling BitSequence for flat
bitmasks) would let row-access algorithms live in arvo-bits and be
reused across BitMatrix64 / 256 / any future backing. Not needed by
current consumers (arvo-graph will use BitMatrix64 directly); add
when a second consumer shape surfaces.
